{
  "doc_id": "8883",
  "text": "There are many clustering protocols which use mobility. A cluster based (CB) [CITATION_1] approach uses binary search to find the RPs. In this work, initially five random CHs get selected. The rest of the nodes join a CH based on the hop count. The mobile sink then visits these CHs. Mobile Sink based adaptive Immune Energy-Efficient clustering Protocol (MSIEEP) [CITATION_2] uses Adaptive Immune Algorithm (AIA) to find the sojourn locations of the mobile sink and the optimum number of CHs. Wang et al. [CITATION_3] proposed two mobile sink based clustering protocols namely, EMCA and MECA to improve the network lifetime. In [CITATION_4] , the authors have used Particle Swarm Optimisation Technique to form a cluster head chain and then used a mobile sink to traverse the cluster heads. Nayak et al. [CITATION_5] use LEACH to find the CHs and then selects a Super Cluster Head (SCH) from them using fuzzy logic. This SCH is responsible for collecting the data from the CHs and then upload this data to a mobile base station. In [CITATION_6] , the authors change the position of the sink in every round to mitigate the hot-spot problem and choose the nodes which are at one-hop distance from the sink as the cluster heads. In [CITATION_7] , the network is divided into clusters called Service Zones from which the data gets collected by the mobile data collectors. This helps in achieving scalability and load balancing of the network. Bio-Inspired Ant Colony Optimisation based Clustering Algorithm (ACO-CA) [CITATION_8] selects the initial CHs based on a variation of LEACH which considers residual energy in each round. If there is another CH in its transmission range, then the one with the higher residual energy gets selected as the final CH. The CHs then get visited by a mobile sink based on Ant-Colony Optimisation technique.",
